::Upgraders vs. Downgraders::In Meyer's Culture Map framework, what is the purpose of "downgraders" (words like "kind of," "maybe," "sort of") in indirect feedback cultures like Vietnam and Thailand?{
~To show uncertainty about the correctness of the feedback #Downgraders aren't about uncertainty—they're about delivery style. The speaker knows the message; downgraders soften the emotional impact to preserve relationships.
=To preserve harmony and save face while still communicating criticism #In indirect feedback cultures, downgraders soften criticism to preserve harmony and save face. Saying "maybe this approach is not quite ideal" communicates the same content as "this is wrong" but protects relationships.
~To make the speaker sound less educated and professional #Downgraders are a professional norm in indirect cultures, not a sign of poor education. They demonstrate cultural competence and emotional intelligence.
~To confuse the listener so they work harder to understand #The purpose isn't confusion—it's face-saving. Members of indirect cultures understand the criticism clearly; downgraders simply reduce the emotional threat.
}

